docs.abstract: In his paintings and pastels, Mr. Petlin reimagined brutal events with subtlety and surrealism in a style neither realistic nor abstract.
docs.snippet: In his paintings and pastels, Mr. Petlin reimagined brutal events with subtlety and surrealism in a style neither realistic nor abstract.
docs.lead_paragraph: Irving Petlin, whose idiosyncratic paintings and pastels reflected a moral commitment to document inhumanity — during the Vietnam War, in the Middle East and on the streets of Paris and Los Angeles, among other examples — died on Sept. 1 at his home on Martha’s Vineyard, in Massachusetts. He was 83.

headline.main: Irving Petlin, Artist Who Recorded Injustice, Dies at 83
headline.print_headline: Irving Petlin, 83, Artist Who Recorded Brutality With Subtle Strokes, Dies

docs.abstract: The former star is using social media savvy, and a total lack of interviews, to control the narrative of protests in the N.F.L.
docs.snippet: The former star is using social media savvy, and a total lack of interviews, to control the narrative of protests in the N.F.L.
docs.lead_paragraph: A tall, unemployed man took his niece to see Serena and Venus Williams play each other at the United States Open on Friday of last week. The man, a free-agent football player clad in a simple black T-shirt, was briefly shown on the video board at Arthur Ashe Stadium to thunderous applause from the crowd. His response was little more than a smile, enough to light up social media with messages of support.

docs.abstract: USAReally might look like any other fledgling news organization. But some cybersecurity experts believe it may be part of a retooled Russian propaganda operation.
docs.snippet: USAReally might look like any other fledgling news organization. But some cybersecurity experts believe it may be part of a retooled Russian propaganda operation.
docs.lead_paragraph: To an untrained eye, USAReally might look like any other fledgling news organization vying for attention in a crowded media landscape. Its website publishes a steady stream of stories on hot-button political issues like race, immigration and income inequality. It has reader polls, a video section and a daily podcast.

headline.main: Is a New Russian Meddling Tactic Hiding in Plain Sight?
headline.print_headline: Russian Website, in Plain View, Stokes the Fire of U.S. Politics

docs.lead_paragraph: WEST HOLLYWOOD, Calif. — There are roles certain actors seem born to play — an echo of facial symmetry, a rhyming of demeanor — and then there is Starr Carter, the high school junior of “The Hate U Give,” and Amandla Stenberg, the young actress who seems to embody her almost from sense memory, as if the performance is actually self portraiture.
